article.headline: McGrady scores 29 vs. former team
article.linkText: Magic win season-high third in a row
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- The Orlando Magic aren't the worst team in the Eastern Conference anymore. Led by Tracy McGrady, Juwan Howard and new starting point guard Rod Strickland, the Magic won their third straight and for the sixth time in eight games Sunday -- 104-93 over the Toronto Raptors. Orlando improved to 7-21, percentage points better than the Atlanta Hawks (7-22). The Magic had a franchise-record 19-game losing streak earlier this season. McGrady credits Strickland for turning the team around. Orlando is 3-0 since he became a starter. "He's doing everything for us. We have a solid veteran point guard. He's the reason why we're playing so well," said McGrady, who scored 29 points. "Thank God we are in the East." Strickland had 14 points, eight assists and six rebounds, Howard had 20 points and 12 rebounds and Drew Gooden added 14 points and 14 rebounds. "I told the coaches when I got here that we just need that one win," said Strickland, who signed with Orlando on Nov. 25. "When you lose that many games it's tough. You have to lack confidence to go through that, but winning breeds confidence." Donyell Marshall had 19 points and 19 rebounds for the Raptors in their fifth loss in six games. Vince Carter added 17 points but had five turnovers and attempted just two free throws. "We didn't play hard," Toronto coach Kevin O'Neill said. "We're very poor defensively right now. Inside we're getting beat up." Toronto struggled with Orlando's zone defense. "It's the worst part of the game right now. It's something that should have never been put in the NBA," Carter said. Orlando outrebounded Toronto 50-44. The undersized Raptors are 6-5 since trading Antonio Davis, their starting center, and Jerome Williams. O'Neill said they're asking too much of rookie Chris Bosh and second-year forward Lonny Baxter, who are forced to play against veterans. "It's going to take a toll on those guys in terms of, not just fatigue, but a lot of things," O'Neill said. Keith Bogans' jumper over Carter gave Orlando an eight-point lead with 8:05 left before Bosh helped bring the Raptors within four by grabbing two offensive rebounds and blocking a shot. Strickland followed with a jumper and McGrady made a 3-pointer to give Orlando a 91-82 lead with 3:44 left, and Strickland grabbed an offensive rebound and made a layup with 58 seconds left to clinch the win. Marshall missed a 3-pointer, and Howard made two free throws to give Orlando a 10-point lead with 36 seconds remaining. McGrady, who played his first three seasons in Toronto, was booed throughout the game. "They ought to get tired of it. Every time they do that, I told them, they're just adding fuel to the fire," he said. "It brings the best out of me and my teammates. It's all love though. They miss me here." Asked if he would consider signing with Toronto if he opts out of his contract next year, McGrady said: "It's too cold outside here for me."

Game notes
McGrady was 12-of-27 from the field. ... Orlando point guard Tyronn Lue returned to the lineup after missing four games because of a strained left hip flexor. ... Fans couldn't drink alcohol because the Air Canada Centre had its liquor license suspended for eight days. ... Toronto committed 16 turnovers.
